Simple Stock Analysis for Long Term Investment¶

Coming from a spirit to inform Indonesian people about investment and the leverage of money, Author built an investing calculator website. The calculator shows how to invest while also paying an installment. For further details, feel free to check the documentation.¶

A. Question(s) and Goal(s)¶

  • If we wanted to invest in a long term interval, how could we reduce the risk while maximizing the return of investment?

  • What is the best way to pick stocks based on criteria from the previous question?

The goal of this analysis is to come up with a group of stocks that are relatively reliable on giving return of investment given the risk involved. The analysis should provide a substantial data to confidently use the stocks for further analysis or use.

B. Data Collection¶

There are a lot of ways to gather historical stock prices with its fundamentals. For this specific analysis, Pandas provided a library to fetch data from multiple sources. The library is called Pandas Data Reader. The library is a wrapper to fetch data such as historical stock prices, GDP of nations, The World economics data, etc. This analysis specifically, Yahoo Finance data is used because it is free and has a huge database of stocks. By avoiding manual work, such as downloading CSV files, the analysis can be used for as many stocks as possible.

import pandas_datareader.data as web

  plt.title(title, fontsize=20)
  plt.xlabel(x_label, fontsize=16)
  plt.ylabel(y_label, fontsize=16)

By using logarithmic return, one can expect more than double the investment. This means if \$1000 was invested back in 2010, the money would worth roughly $2240 today. So, in a span of 10 years, one can expect a 10% return every year on average. Although this is not a guarantee, this should give a rough estimate of the S&P 500 data. Numpy is a great library that contains a lot of powerful mathematical functions and works really well with huge amounts of data. However, in this specific instance, log function should be sufficient.

C. Data Analysis¶

By doing a quick look at the data, there is some work to do before it can be used. One of them is to find the return of investment from each day. This is a necessary step. In investment, the stock price of any given day is not particularly relevant. The price difference of 2 different day prices is.

From the visualization and summary above, now the data looks a little bit easier to read. For instance, although the ROI is going up and down, they are not far from a certain point. It is called oscillation. The middle value of that oscillation is the mean of data, for this example is 1.06. This also means, on average, one can expect 1% ROI every month throughout the 10 years period. Then, the oscillation also has the upper bound and lower bound, and that is called standard deviation or std. With a little modification to the code, they all can be visualized as follows:

In [41]:
def plot_time_series_with_summary(data, title, x_label, y_label):
  plt.figure(figsize=(16,10))
  plt.plot(data, '-')
  plt.gcf().autofmt_xdate()
  plt.axhline(y=data.mean(), label='Mean', color='r')
  plt.fill_between(data.index, (data.mean()-data.std()), (data.mean()+data.std()), color='b', alpha=.1, label='Volatility')
  plt.title(title, fontsize=20)
  plt.xlabel(x_label, fontsize=16)
  plt.ylabel(y_label, fontsize=16)
  plt.legend()
  plt.show()
In [42]:
plot_time_series_with_summary(spy['ROI'], 'ROI of S&P 500 every month since 2011', 'Date', 'ROI in %')

In stock price, the std is called volatility. This is an important metric because when a huge amount of money is involved, less volatile stock is more favorable. Less volatile stock means it is easier to predict because the risk is also lower. Even more, if the data is normally distributed, one can be sure that roughly 68% of the data point will fall inside the volatility area. So, another graph to determine if this time series data is normally distributed. One of many that fits is Q-Q plot.

In [43]:
import statsmodels.api as sm
sm.qqplot(spy, line ='45').show()

Using statsmodels library, Q-Q plot should show if a dataset is normally distributed. If most of the dots fall on the red line, then the distribution is normally distributed. Unfortunately, not this data. So in short, gathering data of a stock in a 10 years period can result in a rough estimation to produce an expectation of what the ROI and risk are using Average and Standard Deviation. However, in order to determine if the risk and ROI are high or low, comparison with other stocks are needed.

D. Bulk Data Collection¶

As stated above, comparison with other stocks is needed to determine if a stock is relatively volatile or not. After gathering some top ETF and stocks in United States, and also some top stocks from Indonesian Stock Exchange, the data is collected and processed exactly the same as before. Then, the data is kept using Pandas DataFrame for further analysis.

In [45]:
tickers_data = [] # Ticker, Average, Std, Data Length
tickers_prices = {} # Ticker data for the Calculator Website
tickers_df = {} # Historical ROI in Pandas DataFrame
for ticker in tickers:
  # Looping through all tickers
  try:
    # Fetch data using Pandas Data Reader and Yahoo Finance
    raw_data = web.DataReader(ticker, 'yahoo', start='2011-01-01', end='2021-01-01')[['Adj Close']].rename(columns={'Adj Close': 'Price'}).copy()
    # Add the next day price for later use to determine ROI per day
    raw_data['d+1'] = raw_data['Price'].shift(-1)
    # Calculate ROI for each day
    raw_data['ROI'] = np.log(raw_data['d+1'] / raw_data['Price']) * 100
    # Convert from Daily RIO into monthly ROI
    monthly_price = raw_data.resample('1M').sum()
    # Determine the upper and lower bound of Margin of Error (Website Purposes)
    monthly_price['lower'] = monthly_price['ROI'] - monthly_price['ROI'].std()
    monthly_price['upper'] = monthly_price['ROI'] + monthly_price['ROI'].std()
    tickers_prices[ticker] = {
        # Saving metrics (Website Purposes)
        'Average': monthly_price['ROI'].mean(),
        'Volatility': monthly_price['ROI'].std(),
        'Data Length': len(monthly_price['ROI']),
        'Data': {
            'Changes': monthly_price['ROI'].values.tolist(),
            'Margin of Error': monthly_price[['lower', 'upper']].values.tolist()
        }
    }
    # Saving the data into the declared valriables above to be used later
    tickers_data.append([ticker, monthly_price['ROI'].mean(), monthly_price['ROI'].std(), len(monthly_price['ROI'])])
    tickers_df[ticker] = monthly_price
  except Exception as e:
    # Catch error in order to prevent interuption of the for loop.
    print(e)
    print(ticker)

Now, it is clear that, although a stock has a huge average ROI month to month, it does not necessarily mean it is the best stock to choose. Especially, when the stock has volatility. For example WSKT.JK Stock, the average ROI is around 1.3% each month. However, during that each month, the price of WSKT.JK stock can increase or decrease for around 16%. It happens also the other way around. High volatility does not necessary mean a huge return. Taking for example INCO stock. With a return less than 0.5% a month, the volatility can go up to 16%. For a long term investment, such volatility is uncessasary high.

The decision can be as arbitrary as possible. Since the purpose of data analysis is to inform the decision maker. So, for this specific data analysis, a stock that has volatility higher than average is considered a high risk stock. That also applies to average ROI, if a stock has an average RIO below the mean, then it is considered less profitable. Therefore, a cut off value can be set at both values which result in below stocks:

G. Conclusion¶

Starting from analyzing the S&P 500 ETF to get a sense of what historical prices can be used for, the output data is felt sufficient for its purpose. By boiling down 34 potential stocks into 14 stocks using volatility and average ROI, the hope is to give a rough estimation of long term investing. However, despite the analysis, the stock market has a huge random aspect backed into it. So, this analysis should only be an input for a larger decision process which consists of many other analyses.
